19 Their beginnings were all ‘Agnus Dei’;
20 there was one word and one manner in all of them,
21 so that there seemed to be complete harmony among them.

28 Thus it was said by one voice;
29 whereupon my master said: “Reply,
30 and ask if one can go up from here”.

43 do not hide from me who you were before death,
44 but tell me, and tell me if I am going the right way to the passage;
45 and let your words be our guides”.

46 “I was Lombard, and I was called Marco;
47 I had knowledge of the world, and I loved that virtue
48 at which everyone nowadays aims his bow.

58 The world is indeed so deserted
59 of every virtue, as you have hinted to me,
60 and pregnant and covered with wickedness;

61 but I pray that you point out the cause to me,
62 so that I may see it and show it to others;
63 for one places it in heaven, and one down here”.

73 Heaven initiates your actions;
74 I do not say all of them, but, even if I did say so,
75 you are given light for good and for evil,

82 Therefore, if the present world goes astray,
83 the cause is in you, in you it must be sought;
84 and I will now be a true guide to you in this.

91 At first it tastes a little bit of good;
92 there it is deceived, and runs after it,
93 if no guide or bridle turns its love.

94 Therefore it was necessary to establish law as a bridle;
95 it was necessary to have a king, who would discern
96 at least the tower of the true city.

97 The laws exist, but who puts his hand to them?
98 No one, because the shepherd who leads
99 can ruminate, but does not have cloven hooves;

109 One has extinguished the other; and the sword
110 has been joined with the shepherd’s staff, and it is wrong
111 for one to go with the other by force;

115 In the land where the Adige and the Po flow,
116 valour and courtesy used to be found,
117 before Frederick had any trouble;

130 “O my Marco”, I said, “you reason well;
131 and now I understand why the sons of Levi
132 were exempted from the inheritance.
